title.rendered: What are the technical features of MySQL?

  • Different backend

title.rendered: What are Heap tables?

content.rendered:
HEAP tables are present in memory and they are used for high speed storage on temporary

basis.

• BLOB or TEXT fields are not allowed

• Only comparison operators can be used =, <,>, = >,=<

• AUTO_INCREMENT is not supported by HEAP tables

• Indexes should be NOT NULL

title.rendered: What does a TIMESTAMP do on UPDATE CURRENT_TIMESTAMP data type?

content.rendered: TIMESTAMP column is updated with Zero when the table is created. UPDATE CURRENT_TIMESTAMP modifier updates the timestamp field to current time whenever there is a change in other fields of the table.

title.rendered: What is the difference between primary key and candidate key?

content.rendered:
Every row of a table is identified uniquely by primary key. There is only one primary key for a table.

Primary Key is also a candidate key. By common convention, candidate key can be designated as primary and which can be used for any foreign key references.

MyISAM Static would be easier to restore in case of corruption.

title.rendered: What is the difference between BLOB AND TEXT?

content.rendered:
A BLOB is a binary large object that can hold a variable amount of data. There are four types of BLOB –

  • TINYBLOB
  • BLOB
  • MEDIUMBLOB and
  • LONGBLOB

They all differ only in the maximum length of the values they can hold.

A TEXT is a case-insensitive BLOB. The four TEXT types

  • TINYTEXT
  • TEXT
  • MEDIUMTEXT and
  • LONGTEXT

They all correspond to the four BLOB types and have the same maximum lengths and storage requirements.

The only difference between BLOB and TEXT types is that sorting and comparison is performed in case-sensitive for BLOB values and case-insensitive for TEXT values.
